  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "### Component\r\n\r\nFoundryup\r\n\r\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\r\n\r\n- [ ] Foundry\r\n- [X] Foundryup\r\n\r\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\r\n\r\n_No response_\r\n\r\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\r\n\r\nfoundryup -C a71e084368822d3a658731d4e5e853213767ec91\r\n\r\n### Operating System\r\n\r\nLinux\r\n\r\n### Describe the bug\r\n\r\nThis commit: https://github.com/foundry-rs/foundry/commit/12ad1c1ffab410fce96d577270cbb167f72fdb6e added a submodule that doesn't go anywhere, now `git submodule update --init --recursive` fails, and specifically fails when running `foundryup` with a previous commit, since it needs to use git.\r\n\r\nHere is the error I get:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfatal: No url found for submodule path 'testdata/lib/forge-std' in .gitmodules\r\nfoundryup: command failed: git submodule update --init --recursive\r\n```\r\n\r\nAs a suggestion, would it be possible to some kind of limited CI test that foundryup actually works so its functionality doesn't regress in the future?",
